{"type": "system", "subtype": "task_notification", "task_id": "a26d984b628300ff4", "tool_use_id": "toolu_vrtx_01JrkPDV2uLQJ5UUZyzsHFeh", "status": "completed", "output_file": "/tmp/claude-1000/-tmp-agent-eval-optimize-2026-07-13-iter-1-cases-compile/2cf90bcd-d8e0-4db3-a279-3d4964966c60/tasks/a26d984b628300ff4.output", "summary": "The audit is complete. Here is a summary of the analysis.\n\n**Scope**: 2 test files, 5 test functions in `tests/compile/correctness_e2e/`.\n\n**Result**: All 5 tests classified as COINCIDENTALLY_CORRECT.\n\nEvery test in this directory follows the same pattern: it uses `compare_two_settings` (directly or via `_compare_sp`) to assert exact dict equality between a compiled configuration (with sequence parallel or async TP fused passes) and a non-compiled standard TP baseline. The key findings:\n\n- **C1 (Weak Oracle)**: All 5 tests use exact dict equality on generated output via `compare_two_settings`, which internally does `assert ref_result == compare_result` at `tests/utils.py:1342`.\n\n- **C2 (Realistic Breakage)**: The compiled paths (SP, async TP, fused GEMM+comm, fused norm/act quant) use fundamentally different kernel dispatch chains and numeric reduction orders than the unfused TP baseline. PyTorch/cuBLAS changes realistically alter these floating-point results.\n\n- **C3 (No Strong Contract)**: All tests fall under **Not Strong #5** (\"Sequence parallel, async TP, or fused distributed compile-pass parity against an unfused baseline\") and **Not Strong #2** (\"Non-compiled vs compiled mode parity hidden inside `compare_two_settings`\"). No `VLLM_BATCH_INVARIANT` is set in any test file or conftest.py. No test asserts that the feature (SP/async TP) actually executed.\n\n**Output files**:\n- `/tmp/agent-eval/optimize-2026-07-13-iter-1/cases/compile/audit-cc.json` -- 5 COINCIDENTALLY_CORRECT candidates\n- `/tmp/agent-eval/optimize-2026-07-13-iter-1/cases/compile/audit-not-cc.json` -- 0 candidates\n- `/tmp/agent-eval/optimize-2026-07-13